                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" id="anarchism_sng_1" fkcefr="c2" hclass="sense" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">the political belief that laws and governments are not necessary; a political force or movement based on this belief</span></span><span class="topic-g"><span class="prefix">Topics </span><a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/war-and-conflict?level=c2" title="Topic war-and-conflict"><span class="topic" href="l2:politics_and_society:war_and_conflict?cefr=c2"><span class="topic_name">War and conflict</span><span class="topic_cefr">c2</span></span></a><span class="sep">,</span> <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/politics?level=c2" title="Topic politics"><span class="topic" href="l2:politics_and_society:politics?cefr=c2"><span class="topic_name">Politics</span><span class="topic_cefr">c2</span></span></a></span><div class="collapse" htag="div" hclass="collapse"><span class="unbox" unbox="wordorigin" id="anarchism_unbox_1"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">mid 17th cent.: from Greek <span class="ei">anarkhos</span> ‘without a chief’ (from <span class="ei">an-</span> ‘without’ + <span class="ei">arkhos</span> ‘chief, ruler’) + <span class="eb">-ism</span>; later influenced by French <span class="ei">anarchisme</span>.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
